04997nam a22007095i 9780691187044DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911870447 a10.1515/97806911870442doi  a(DE-B1597)501686  a(OCoLC)1076414569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a330.967112231 aRoitman, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFiscal Disobedience :bAn Anthropology of Economic Regulation in Central Africa /cJanet Roitman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIn-Formation00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Introduction: An Anthropology of Regulation and Fiscal Relations -- tChapter Two. Incivisme Fiscal -- tChapter Three. Tax-Price as a Technique of Government -- tChapter Four. Unsanctioned Wealth, or the Productivity of Debt -- tChapter Five. Fixing the Moving Targets of Regulation -- tChapter Six. The Unstable Terms of Regulatory Practice -- tChapter Seven. The Pluralization of Regulatory Authority -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFiscal Disobedience represents a novel approach to the question of citizenship amid the changing global economy and the fiscal crisis of the nation-state. Focusing on economic practices in the Chad Basin of Africa, Janet Roitman combines thorough ethnographic fieldwork with sophisticated analysis of key ideas of political economy to examine the contentious nature of fiscal relationships between the state and its citizens. She argues that citizenship is being redefined through a renegotiation of the rights and obligations inherent in such economic relationships. The book centers on a civil disobedience movement that arose in Cameroon beginning in 1990 ostensibly to counter state fiscal authority--a movement dubbed Opération Villes Mortes by the opposition and incivisme fiscal by the government (which for its part was eager to suggest that participants were less than legitimate citizens, failing in their civic duties). Contrary to standard approaches, Roitman examines this conflict as a "productive moment" that, rather than involving the outright rejection of regulatory authority, questioned the intelligibility of its exercise. Although both militarized commercial networks (associated with such activities trading in contraband goods including drugs, ivory, and guns) and highly organized gang-based banditry do challenge state authority, they do not necessarily undermine state power. Contrary to depictions of the African state as "weak" or "failed," this book demonstrates how the state in Africa manages to reconstitute its authority through networks that have emerged in the interstices of the state system. It also shows how those networks partake of the same epistemological grounding as does the state. Indeed, both state and nonstate practices of governing refer to a common "ethic of illegality," which explains how illegal activities are understood as licit or reasonable conduct.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTax evasionzCameroon. 0aTaxationzCameroon. 0aWealthxSocial aspectszCameroon. 0aWealthxSocial aspectszChad Basin Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187044zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187044.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton Uni